## Rule: Base behavior for metro-tax-lookup

You are helping build a public, static-data web tool that makes **Arapahoe-focused property tax and metro-district context** easier to understand.

- **North star:** Push toward an experience that feels **markedly more helpful** than county sites and PDFs alone (clarity, speed, privacy, explanation, fewer dead ends). That is a **direction**, not a pass/fail gate on every line of copy - but if the whole product drifts into "thin clone" territory, step back and **re-center** (change course, cut scope, or sharpen what is unique).

Implementation can be precise. **User-facing copy and layout should lean away from** county-site tone and spreadsheet vibes - **aim for** something people actually want to use.

### Core preferences

- Use clear, maintainable, well-typed code.
- Favor functional components and hooks when using React.
- Design mobile-first, responsive layouts with a single, high-contrast light theme.
- **UI/UX and feel:** Treat this as a **real product**, not a bare form dump. Aim for **great** interaction design - clear hierarchy, generous spacing, responsive behavior, helpful feedback, and polish. The overall vibe should be **light and engaging** - **fun** is a valid target alongside accessible and trustworthy.

### Pointer (cursor) affordances

- **Hover must read as clickable:** Any control that responds to click or tap (native or custom `button`, `a`, disclosure/accordion headers, segment toggles, hub card links, icon-only controls, draggable handles, etc.) must show an explicit **`cursor-pointer`** on the interactive surface in Tailwind (`className` on the element that receives the click, or a parent that covers the full hit target). Do not leave the default arrow on something that is obviously interactive.
- **Chevrons and icons inside buttons** inherit from the parent; ensure the **parent** button/link has `cursor-pointer` so hovering the caret matches the rest of the control.
- **Disabled:** Use **`cursor-not-allowed`** (and `disabled:` styles) when the control is visibly disabled; do not use `cursor-pointer` there.
- **Text fields:** Keep default text cursor on inputs and textareas; do not force `cursor-pointer` on plain inputs.

### Information hierarchy (progressive disclosure)

- **Primary first:** The main payoff (visualization, totals, the core widget) should appear **before** supporting context so users are not buried in fine print on the way to the answer.
- **Supporting detail below:** Metadata (e.g. matched PIN, TAG id, verification links), extra links, and explanatory accordions belong **under** the primary content for users who want to dig deeper - not stacked above tiles, charts, or key results.
- **Avoid redundancy:** Do not repeat the same idea in a subsection heading and the parent card title; one clear label per region is enough.
- **Light separators:** Do not use extra horizontal rules or heavy borders between adjacent blocks that are already part of one flow (e.g. between a help accordion and a mode toggle). Separate only when it genuinely aids scanning.

### Accessibility (critical)

- **Accessibility is a first-class requirement**, not a visual polish pass. The app is for the **general public**, including people who **do not** navigate primarily by sight.
- **Keyboard and focus:** Every flow must be fully operable with keyboard only - tab order that matches reading order, no keyboard traps, visible focus states, and correct use of native controls (`button`, `a`, `input`) or equivalent roles and keyboard handlers for custom widgets.
- **Screen readers and assistive tech:** Provide proper names, roles, and states; associate labels with fields; surface errors and dynamic results (`role="alert"`, `aria-live`, regions) so non-visual users get the same outcomes as sighted users.
- **Do not rely on** color alone, hover-only cues, or pointer-only gestures for essential information or actions.
- **Forms and search:** Use real `<form>` + submit semantics where users expect Enter to act; keep labels, hints, and validation perceivable and programmatically tied to inputs.
- **Baseline:** Meet or exceed **WCAG 2.1 AA**; when in doubt, choose the more inclusive option.

### Framework-specific

- Follow established best practices for Next.js/React components and Tailwind CSS utility usage.
- **JSX prose / whitespace:** Inline tags (`<strong>`, `<dfn>`, etc.) plus line breaks can drop spaces between words. Use explicit `{" "}` after closing inline tags before more text; see `.cursor/rules/jsx-whitespace.mdc`.

### Engineering principles

- Follow DRY (don't repeat yourself) and KISS (keep it simple).
- Apply YAGNI (don't build features or abstractions until they are needed).
- Observe at least the OWASP Top 10 security guidelines in design and implementation.
- Accessibility expectations are spelled out under **Accessibility (critical)** above; WCAG 2.1 AA is the minimum bar.

**Review and audit responses (any type):** When the user asks for a **review, audit, final check, pre-commit check, a11y/contrast/SR/keyboard pass, security review, or similar**, respond **only with gaps, risks, and follow-ups** — things they might have **missed** or should **verify manually**. Do **not** summarize what is already fine, what passed, that the build or lint succeeded (unless the user explicitly asked for a command result), balanced pros/cons, or "what's good" / "already in good shape" sections. Those bury the signal. If there is **nothing** to flag after a sincere pass, say so in **one short sentence** (e.g. "No issues to flag from this pass.").

The same **negatives-only** rule applies to the scoped audits below (DRY, KISS, YAGNI, OWASP, etc.): only actionable or questionable items, not praise or reassurance lists.

### Project-specific rules

- Avoid adding a database or user accounts unless explicitly requested by the user.
- Prefer simple, static data files checked into the repo when possible.
- **Never use smart quotes or smart apostrophes** (e.g. curly " " ' '). Use only straight/ASCII quotes and apostrophes (U+0022, U+0027) in code, docs, and copy. This avoids encoding mismatches, broken search/replace, and inconsistent display.

### Audience, tone, and language (user-facing)

- **Plain language (levy / mills OK; "levy lines" pattern not):** Avoid accountant-style **"levy lines" / "district lines" / "mills lines"** stacked phrasing in user-facing strings; **levy** and **mills** are fine when clear. Intent is **spirit** (readable for the public), not a ban on every word. See `.cursor/rules/plain-language-no-lines-jargon.mdc`.
- **Who this is for:** The **general public** - including people whose eyes glaze over at **financial statements, spreadsheets, and dense government forms**. Write for them first. When copy reads like it was pasted from a county assessor or treasurer page, **consider rewriting** for warmth and clarity (exceptions are fine when accuracy requires it).
- **How it should feel:** **Light, clear, and inviting** - quick to understand, low cognitive load, **enlightening** without being flip or fear-based (skip bait like "shocking" or "alarming" your bill). Prefer **everyday words**, short lines, and a calm confidence that the tool is on the user's side.
- **Steer away from in primary UI** (headings, labels, buttons, hints, errors, empty states, hub cards, main flows): heavy **county website echo** (their jargon as the main story, or "same as the county search" as the value prop) and **piles of tax/assessor jargon** when plain language would do. **Prefer** explaining in human terms in the flow; **save** bureaucracy-shaped detail for people who want depth.
- **When jargon is needed:** Lead with **plain language in the UI**; put **precise terms, methodology, or citations** on **`/sources`** (or another dedicated in-app explanation), with a **first-use definition or footnote** there when you introduce something technical. Occasional terms in the UI are OK if wrapped in plain English.
- **Human-friendly documentation:** Put methodology, provenance, citations, audit guidance, and **definitions of technical terms** on the **in-app Sources** page (`/sources`). The repo **README** stays **technical** (developers, GitHub, pipeline). Do **not** paste long narrative methodology into README - **cross-link `/sources`**. On Sources, spell out or link jargon on **first substantive use** (e.g. **JSON** with an in-page definition or footnote), not only in README.
- **Documentation when you change things:** Any addition or change that affects how the app works, what data it uses, how it is built or deployed, or how users should interpret results must include updates to **README.md** and/or **`src/app/sources/page.tsx`** as appropriate before the work is considered complete. README: setup, pipeline, file paths. `/sources`: narrative, citations, and **plain explanations** for readers who want depth. If unsure, prefer `/sources` for human narrative and README for a short cross-link only.

### General AI behavior

- **Default to short replies.** A few sentences or one short paragraph is often enough. Do not fire-hose lists of options, sub-options, or tangents. The user will ask to elaborate when they want depth.
- **Answer the actual question** they asked; do not expand into a survey of alternatives unless they asked for options or a comparison.
- Keep code and explanations concise.
- Explain non-trivial changes or design choices briefly when suggesting edits.
- When the user asks a question, answer it directly before proposing or performing implementation work.
- Prefer the user to run terminal/CLI commands; only suggest commands, and assume non-trivial commands may be rejected or run manually by the user.
- Do not run any `git` commands (status/diff/log/commit/push/etc.) unless the user explicitly asks you to run them.
